We now move forward to map the design space of LSM-trees in a way that allows to accurately predict the impact of the various design decisions. To do so, we model lookup and update cost in closed-form expressions with respect to all the tuning knobs in the Monkey design space. We also demonstrate analytically that Monkey dominates the state-of-the-art designs.

**Modeling Zero-Result Lookup Cost ($R$).** To derive a closed-form expression for the zero-result lookup cost $R$ in Monkey, we plug the optimal false positive rates in Equations 5 and 6 into Equation 4, simplify, and rearrange. The complete derivation is in Appendix B.1, and the result is Equation 7. This equation assumes a fixed entry size (we lift this restriction in Appendix C).

$$
R=R_{filtered}+R_{unfiltered}
$$

$$
R_{filtered}=\begin{cases}
\frac{T^{\frac{T}{T-1}}}{T-1}\cdot e^{-\frac{M_{filters}}{N}\cdot\ln(2)^2\cdot T^{L_{unfiltered}}},&\text{with leveling}\\
T^{\frac{T}{T-1}}\cdot e^{-\frac{M_{filters}}{N}\cdot\ln(2)^2\cdot T^{L_{unfiltered}}},&\text{with tiering}
\end{cases}
$$

$$
R_{unfiltered}=\begin{cases}
L_{unfiltered},&\text{with leveling}\\
L_{unfiltered}\cdot(T-1),&\text{with tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{7}
$$

To demystify Equation 7, note that the additive terms $R_{filtered}$ and $R_{unfiltered}$ correspond to the average number of runs probed in the levels with and without filters respectively. Also recall that when the size ratio $T$ is set to 2, tiering and leveling behave identically, and so the two versions of the equation for tiering and leveling produce the same result.

$$
L_{unfiltered}=\begin{cases}
0,&M_{threshold}\leq M_{filters}\\
\left\lceil\log_T\left(\frac{M_{threshold}}{M_{filters}}\right)\right\rceil,&\frac{M_{threshold}}{T^L}\leq M_{filters}\leq M_{threshold}\\
L,&0\leq M_{filters}\leq\frac{M_{threshold}}{T^L}
\end{cases}
$$

$$
M_{threshold}=\frac{N}{\ln(2)^2}\cdot\frac{\ln(T)}{T-1}
\tag{8}
$$

Next, we derive Equation 8, which gives the number of deeper levels for which there are no filters. To do so, we first derive the threshold value $M_{threshold}$ of main memory at which the FPR of filters at the last level (i.e., Level $L$) converge to 1 (see bottom of Equation 8). The complete derivation is in Appendix B.1. The optimal value of $L_{unfiltered}$ given by Equation 8 can be plugged into Equation 7 to compute $R$.

**Modeling Worst-Case Non-Zero-Result Lookup Cost ($V$).** Using Equation 7 for the average worst-case zero-result lookup cost $R$, we can now also model the average worst-case cost $V$ of a non-zero-result lookup, which finds the target key in the oldest run. To model this cost, we subtract $p_L$, the FPR of the oldest run’s filter, and instead add 1 to account for reading one page of this run.

$$V=R-p_L+1\tag{9}$$

**Modeling Worst-Case Update Cost ($W$).** To model the worst-case update cost, we assume a worst-case update pattern where an entry is updated at most once within a period of $N$ application writes. Thus, no entry is eliminated before getting merged into the largest level. Using arithmetic series, we model the amortized worst-case number of merge operations that an entry participates in per level as $\approx\frac{T-1}{T}$ and $\approx\frac{T-1}{2}$ with tiering and leveling respectively. We multiply this by $L$ since each entry moves through $L$ levels, and we divide by $B$ since each write I/O moves $B$ entries from the original runs to the resulting run. Finally, we account for reading the original runs in order to merge them, and also that write I/Os to secondary storage on some storage devices (e.g., flash) are more expensive than reads, by multiplying by $(1+\phi)$, where $\phi$ is the cost ratio between writes and reads. The overall I/O cost is captured by Equation 10. When $T$ is set to 2, tiering and leveling behave identically, so the two parts of the equation produce the same result.

$$
W=\begin{cases}
\frac{L}{B}\cdot\frac{T-1}{2}\cdot(1+\phi),&\text{with leveling}\\
\frac{L}{B}\cdot\frac{T-1}{T}\cdot(1+\phi),&\text{with tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{10}
$$

**Modeling Worst-Case Range Lookup Cost ($Q$).** A range lookup involves doing $L$ or $L\cdot(T-1)$ disk seeks (one per run) for leveling and tiering respectively. Each seek is followed by a sequential scan. The cumulative number of pages scanned over all runs is $s\cdot\frac{N}{B}$, where $s$ is the average proportion of all entries included in range lookups. Hence, the overall range lookup cost $Q$ in terms of pages reads is as follows.

$$
Q=\begin{cases}
s\cdot\frac{N}{B}+L,&\text{with leveling}\\
s\cdot\frac{N}{B}+L\cdot(T-1),&\text{with tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{11}
$$

**Modeling the State of the Art.** We now derive an analogous model for existing state-of-the-art designs. The models for $V$, $W$, and $Q$ are the same as for Monkey, namely Equations 9, 10 and 11, because Monkey’s core design does not alter these operations. To model the worst-case expected point lookup I/O cost, we set all false positive rates $p_1,p_2...p_L$ in Equation 3 to be equal to each other. The complete derivation and resulting closed-form Equation 26 are in Appendix E.

**Monkey Dominates Existing Designs.** We now have two cost models for lookup cost with Monkey (Equations 7 and 8) and with the state of the art (Equation 26). In Figure 7, we compare Monkey against the state of the art by plotting the zero-result lookup cost as we vary $M_{filters}$ with these equations. Although we keep the terms in the figure general, the curves are drawn for an LSM-tree with 512 TB of data; the number of entries $N$ is $2^{35}$, the entry size $E$ is 16 bytes, the size ratio $T$ is 4, the buffer size $B\cdot P\cdot E$ is 2 MB, and we vary $M_{filters}$ from 0 to 35 GB.

Monkey dominates the state of the art in terms of lookup cost for any overall amount of main memory allocated to the filters. The reason is that it allocates this memory optimally among the Bloom filters to minimize the average number of read I/Os per lookup.

As $M_{filters}$ in Figure 7 approaches 0, Monkey and the state of the art both degenerate into an LSM-tree with no Bloom filters, and so their curves meet. The term $X$ in the figure is used to adjust the terms for leveling and tiering. The two curves look identical except that the curve for tiering is vertically stretched upwards by a factor of $T-1$ since there are $T-1$ more runs per level.

**Figure 7:** Monkey dominates the state of the art in terms of lookup cost $R$ for all values of $M_{filters}$.

sections.translationMarkdown:
现在进一步刻画 LSM-tree 的设计空间，以便准确预测各种设计决策的影响。为此，我们针对 Monkey 设计空间中的所有调优旋钮，使用闭式表达式对查找成本和更新成本建模。我们还从分析上证明 Monkey 优于现有最佳设计。

**零结果查找成本（$R$）建模。** 为推导 Monkey 中零结果查找成本 $R$ 的闭式表达式，我们将公式 5 和公式 6 中的最优假阳性率代入公式 4，然后化简并重新整理。完整推导见附录 B.1，结果为公式 7。该公式假设条目大小固定；附录 C 解除了这一限制。

$$
R=R_{filtered}+R_{unfiltered}
$$

$$
R_{filtered}=\begin{cases}
\frac{T^{\frac{T}{T-1}}}{T-1}\cdot e^{-\frac{M_{filters}}{N}\cdot\ln(2)^2\cdot T^{L_{unfiltered}}},&\text{采用 leveling}\\
T^{\frac{T}{T-1}}\cdot e^{-\frac{M_{filters}}{N}\cdot\ln(2)^2\cdot T^{L_{unfiltered}}},&\text{采用 tiering}
\end{cases}
$$

$$
R_{unfiltered}=\begin{cases}
L_{unfiltered},&\text{采用 leveling}\\
L_{unfiltered}\cdot(T-1),&\text{采用 tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{7}
$$

为使公式 7 更易理解，需要注意：两个相加项 $R_{filtered}$ 和 $R_{unfiltered}$ 分别对应在有过滤器层和无过滤器层中探测的平均 run 数量。还应回想一下，当大小比率 $T$ 设为 2 时，tiering 和 leveling 的行为相同，因此公式中针对二者的两个版本会给出相同结果。

$$
L_{unfiltered}=\begin{cases}
0,&M_{threshold}\leq M_{filters}\\
\left\lceil\log_T\left(\frac{M_{threshold}}{M_{filters}}\right)\right\rceil,&\frac{M_{threshold}}{T^L}\leq M_{filters}\leq M_{threshold}\\
L,&0\leq M_{filters}\leq\frac{M_{threshold}}{T^L}
\end{cases}
$$

$$
M_{threshold}=\frac{N}{\ln(2)^2}\cdot\frac{\ln(T)}{T-1}
\tag{8}
$$

接下来推导公式 8，它给出了没有过滤器的较深层数量。为此，首先推导主存阈值 $M_{threshold}$；在该阈值处，最后一层（即第 $L$ 层）过滤器的 FPR 趋近于 1，见公式 8 的底部。完整推导见附录 B.1。将公式 8 给出的 $L_{unfiltered}$ 最优值代入公式 7，即可计算 $R$。

**最坏情况非零结果查找成本（$V$）建模。** 利用公式 7 给出的平均最坏情况零结果查找成本 $R$，现在还可以对非零结果查找的平均最坏情况成本 $V$ 建模；该查找会在最旧的 run 中找到目标键。为了对这一成本建模，我们减去最旧 run 的过滤器 FPR $p_L$，再加 1，以计入读取该 run 一个页面的成本。

$$V=R-p_L+1\tag{9}$$

**最坏情况更新成本（$W$）建模。** 为了对最坏情况更新成本建模，我们假设一种最坏情况更新模式：在 $N$ 次应用写入期间，每个条目至多更新一次。因此，任何条目在被合并到最大层之前都不会被消除。利用等差数列，我们将一个条目在每层参与合并操作的摊销最坏情况次数建模为：tiering 约为 $\frac{T-1}{T}$，leveling 约为 $\frac{T-1}{2}$。由于每个条目都会经过 $L$ 层，因此将该值乘以 $L$；又因为每次写 I/O 会将 $B$ 个条目从原始 run 移动到结果 run，因此再除以 $B$。最后，还要考虑为了合并而读取原始 run 的开销，以及在某些存储设备（例如闪存）上对二级存储执行写 I/O 比读 I/O 更昂贵这一事实。因此乘以 $(1+\phi)$，其中 $\phi$ 是写成本与读成本之比。总 I/O 成本如公式 10 所示。当 $T$ 设为 2 时，tiering 与 leveling 行为相同，所以公式的两个分支会产生相同结果。

$$
W=\begin{cases}
\frac{L}{B}\cdot\frac{T-1}{2}\cdot(1+\phi),&\text{采用 leveling}\\
\frac{L}{B}\cdot\frac{T-1}{T}\cdot(1+\phi),&\text{采用 tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{10}
$$

**最坏情况范围查找成本（$Q$）建模。** 对于 leveling 和 tiering，一次范围查找分别需要执行 $L$ 次或 $L\cdot(T-1)$ 次磁盘寻道，每个 run 一次。每次寻道之后都会执行顺序扫描。在所有 run 上扫描的累计页数为 $s\cdot\frac{N}{B}$，其中 $s$ 是范围查找平均包含的全部条目比例。因此，以读取页数计量的总范围查找成本 $Q$ 如下。

$$
Q=\begin{cases}
s\cdot\frac{N}{B}+L,&\text{采用 leveling}\\
s\cdot\frac{N}{B}+L\cdot(T-1),&\text{采用 tiering}
\end{cases}
\tag{11}
$$

**现有最佳方案建模。** 现在为现有最佳设计推导一个类似模型。$V$、$W$ 和 $Q$ 的模型与 Monkey 相同，即公式 9、公式 10 和公式 11，因为 Monkey 的核心设计并未改变这些操作。为了对点查找的最坏情况预期 I/O 成本建模，我们令公式 3 中所有假阳性率 $p_1,p_2...p_L$ 彼此相等。完整推导及由此得到的闭式公式 26 见附录 E。

**Monkey 优于现有设计。** 现在，我们分别有了 Monkey 的查找成本模型（公式 7 和公式 8）以及现有最佳方案的查找成本模型（公式 26）。图 7 使用这些公式，在改变 $M_{filters}$ 时绘制零结果查找成本，从而对 Monkey 和现有最佳方案进行比较。尽管图中各项采用了一般形式，但曲线对应的是一棵数据量为 512 TB 的 LSM-tree：条目数量 $N$ 为 $2^{35}$，条目大小 $E$ 为 16 字节，大小比率 $T$ 为 4，缓冲区大小 $B\cdot P\cdot E$ 为 2 MB，而 $M_{filters}$ 从 0 变化到 35 GB。

无论分配给过滤器的主存总量是多少，Monkey 在查找成本方面都优于现有最佳方案。原因在于，它在 Bloom 过滤器之间最优分配这些主存，从而最小化每次查找的平均读 I/O 次数。

当图 7 中的 $M_{filters}$ 趋近于 0 时，Monkey 与现有最佳方案都会退化为没有 Bloom 过滤器的 LSM-tree，因此两条曲线相交。图中的 $X$ 用于针对 leveling 和 tiering 调整相应项。两条曲线看起来相同，区别只在于：由于 tiering 每层多出 $T-1$ 个 run，其曲线在竖直方向上被拉伸了 $T-1$ 倍。

**图 7：** 对于 $M_{filters}$ 的所有取值，Monkey 在查找成本 $R$ 方面均优于现有最佳方案。
